Exploratory Data Analysis - Customer Satisfaction

Introduction

Customer satisfaction is a key measurement of success for many companies. This exploratory data analysis (EDA) dives into survey data obtained from an airline company, available on Kaggle here. The primary objective is to uncover valuable insights that can assist the airline company in better understanding its customers, identifying patterns, and informing strategic decisions.

1. Data Loading and Initial Inspection

We start the analysis by loading the dataset and perform an initial inspection. We examine the data structure, check for missing values, incorrect data types and other potential issues, making necessary preparations for further exploration.This helps us better understand the data we are working with.

2. Data Cleaning

As we prepare our data for analysis, we address instances where information is missing, ensuring a more complete dataset with enhanced quality and usability.

3. Exploring Satisfaction & Age

In this section, we investigate customer satisfaction and age demographics to discover patterns and trends. This helps us better understand our customers and find opportunities to make improvements, whether by enhancing our services or targeting specific customer groups.

4. Services & Correlation With Satisfaction

This part of the analysis focuses on identifying the factors that correlate with customer satisfaction. By understanding these correlations, we can determine which services contribute the most to a positive customer experience. This helps us prioritize areas for improvement so we can effectively work towards increasing overall customer satisfaction.

5. Key Findings

Here we highlight the most significant insights from our analysis, focusing on the factors that most strongly influence customer satisfaction and identifying key demographic trends.

6. Recommendations

Based on our key findings, this section offers suggestions for service improvements and targeted initiatives to enhance customer satisfaction.

3.

Lets look at satisfaction.

overall_satisfaction <- clean_airline %>%
  group_by(satisfaction) %>%
  summarize(proportion = n() / nrow(.) * 100)

ggplot(overall_satisfaction, aes(x = '', y = proportion, fill = satisfaction)) +
  geom_col() +
  labs(x = 'satisfaction', y = 'proportion')

Looking at the overall satisfaction level, almost 55% of the airline customers are satisfied.

To determine if the observed differences in customer satisfaction are genuine, we run a statistical test.

This test is designed to assess whether there is a statistically significant difference between the proportions of satisfied and dissatisfied customers. We start with the null hypothesis (H0) that assumes there is no actual difference in these proportions, suggesting that any observed variation might simply be due to random chance. The objective of the test is to evaluate the data and determine whether there is enough evidence to reject this null hypothesis, and confirming a significant difference in satisfaction levels.

# Step 1: Count the number of successes (satisfied customers)
num_satisfied <- sum(clean_airline$satisfaction == "satisfied")

# Step 2: Count the total number of trials (total number of customers)
total_customers <- nrow(clean_airline)

# Step 3: Perform the Z-test for Proportion
z_test_result <- prop.test(x = num_satisfied, n = total_customers, p = 0.5, correct = FALSE)

# Step 4: Print the result
print(z_test_result)
## 
##  1-sample proportions test without continuity correction
## 
## data:  num_satisfied out of total_customers, null probability 0.5
## X-squared = 1164, df = 1, p-value < 2.2e-16
## alternative hypothesis: true p is not equal to 0.5
## 95 percent confidence interval:
##  0.5446938 0.5501159
## sample estimates:
##         p 
## 0.5474063

As we can see from the test, the p-value is extremely close to zero (0.000000000000000022) which tells us that there is in fact a significant difference in satisfaction.

Lets look at satisfaction levels within each class.

class_satisfaction <- clean_airline %>%
  group_by(Class, satisfaction) %>%
  summarize(count = n()) %>%
  mutate(proportion = count / sum(count))

ggplot(class_satisfaction, aes(Class, proportion, fill = satisfaction)) +
  geom_col()

Here it becomes clear that customers travelling in Business Class are overall very satisfied. Unfortunately, customers in Economy and Economy Plus are not as satisfied with their experience.

Lets break it down further and look at age.

summary(clean_airline$Age)
##    Min. 1st Qu.  Median    Mean 3rd Qu.    Max. 
##    7.00   27.00   40.00   39.43   51.00   85.00
ggplot(clean_airline, aes(x = Age)) +
    geom_histogram(binwidth = 1, fill = 'Slategray3')

From the summary statistics we can see that minimum age is 7, maximum age is 85 and the median age is 40. If we look at the distribution of age between customers, we can see that most of them are between the ages of 20-60.

Now lets divide customers into age groups

clean_airline <- clean_airline %>%
  mutate(Age.Group = case_when(
    Age >= 7 & Age <= 14 ~ '0-14',
    Age > 14 & Age <= 20 ~ '15-20',
    Age > 20 & Age <= 30 ~ '21-30',
    Age > 30 & Age <= 40 ~ '31-40',
    Age > 40 & Age <= 50 ~ '41-50',
    Age > 50 & Age <= 60 ~ '51-60',
    Age > 60 & Age <= 65 ~ '61-65',
    Age > 65 ~ '65+',
    TRUE ~ NA_character_
  ))

age_proportion <- clean_airline %>%
  group_by(Age.Group, satisfaction) %>%
  summarise(count = n()) %>%
  mutate(proportion = count / sum(count))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'Age.Group'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.

Lets look at how satisfaction differ between age groups within Business Class.

age_proportion <- clean_airline %>%
  filter(Class == 'Business') %>%
  group_by(Age.Group, satisfaction) %>%
  summarise(count = n()) %>%
  mutate(proportion = count / sum(count))
## `summarise()` has grouped output by 'Age.Group'. You can override using the
## `.groups` argument.
ggplot(age_proportion, aes(x = Age.Group, y = proportion, fill = satisfaction)) +
    geom_col() +
    theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 45, hjust = 1)) +
    scale_x_discrete()

Looking at satisfaction levels between age groups within Business Class, we can clearly see that the least satisfied customers are between 0-14 and 65+, and customers between 61-65 are not as satisfied as the other age groups.

4.

To investigate what services are associated with satisfaction, lets check the correlation between satisfaction and the different types of services within Business Class.

clean_airline_numeric <- clean_airline %>%
  filter(Class == 'Business') %>%
  mutate(satisfaction = ifelse(satisfaction == 'satisfied',1,0)) %>%
  select_if(is.numeric)

correlation_matrix <- cor(clean_airline_numeric)

satisfaction_correlation <- correlation_matrix["satisfaction", ]
satisfaction_correlation <- satisfaction_correlation[order(satisfaction_correlation, decreasing = TRUE)]

satisfaction_correlation <- satisfaction_correlation[names(satisfaction_correlation) != "satisfaction"]
par(mar = c(11,5,5,5))
barplot(satisfaction_correlation, main = "Correlations with Satisfaction",
        ylab = "Correlation", col = ifelse(satisfaction_correlation > 0, "palegreen", "salmon"),
        las = 2, cex.names = 0.8)

Here we can see that Inflight entertainment and Ease of Online Booking shows the highest positive correlation with overall satisfaction, even if its only moderately correlated. The green bars indicate services positively correlated with satisfaction, suggesting their beneficial impact on the customer experience. In contrast, red bars highlight services negatively correlated with satisfaction, pointing to areas that might lower the overall customer experience.

5. Key findings

  • Inflight Entertainment and Ease of Online Booking shows the highest positive correlation with overall satisfaction, suggesting its importance in enhancing the customer experience.

  • Satisfaction levels vary significantly between classes, with Business Class passengers being notably more satisfied than Economy and Economy Plus passengers.

  • Within Business Class, passengers aged 0-14 and 65+ are the only age groups that shows a higher dissatisfaction.

6. Recommendations:

  • Explore different services in-depth to understand how specific improvements could positively impact overall satisfaction.

  • Address areas causing dissatisfaction among Economy and Economy Plus passengers to improve overall satisfaction.

  • Implement targeted improvements for age groups showing lower satisfaction in Business Class.
